NOTE: Many packages in R have a function called select() including base R, so it is not unusual for R to get confused which select() you are trying to use (later on we will learn where this confusion comes from). If you ever see an error that select() isnt working as you expect, re-write it explicitly as dplyr::select() to clearly tell R that you want the dplyr function.

NOTE2: The library tidylog is actually modifying dplyr functions so that they also print out various informative messages. Therefore, if you specify dplyr::<function> these messages will NOT appear because the dplyr versions will be used. If you specify tidylog::<function> you can ensure messages DO appear. Because we loaded tidylog AFTER tidyverse, the default versions R assumes you want to use are tidylogs functions if you do not explicitly specify.

Setup

We will learn the fundamentals of dplyr using the built-in R dataset CO2. This dataset is not in the best default format, so we will define it as a tibble for our use, but save it as a new variable CO2_tibble.

# Create a new lowercase variable. __NEVER__ overwrite base R variables. 
# CO2 <- as.tibble(CO2) is _very bad._ Don't do this.
CO2_tibble <- as_tibble(CO2)
head(CO2_tibble)
## # A tibble: 6 x 5
##   Plant Type   Treatment   conc uptake
##   <ord> <fct>  <fct>      <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 Qn1   Quebec nonchilled    95   16  
## 2 Qn1   Quebec nonchilled   175   30.4
## 3 Qn1   Quebec nonchilled   250   34.8
## 4 Qn1   Quebec nonchilled   350   37.2
## 5 Qn1   Quebec nonchilled   500   35.3
## 6 Qn1   Quebec nonchilled   675   39.2

This dataset contains data from an experiment on the cold tolerance of the grass species Echinochloa crus-galli. The CO2 uptake of six plants from Quebec and six plants from Mississippi was measured at several levels of ambient CO2 concentration. Half the plants of each type were chilled overnight before the experiment was conducted.

Messages from tidylog

As you can see in the setup R chunk of this document, tidylog has been loaded for you. This fairly amazing library provides you with direct feedback about what goes on under the hood of tidyverse operations.

Question 12

Create a new tibble called quebec that contains only plants from Quebec. Work with this tibble to determine the following answers. Your answers to the questions will simply be the displayed output from your code.

  • What is the mean (function mean()) uptake for Quebec plants? Use summarize(), no dollar signs!
CO2_tibble %>%
  filter(Type == "Quebec") -> quebec
## filter: removed 42 rows (50%), 42 rows remaining
#Defined the refined dataset as quebec, a new tibble used in Q12.

quebec %>%
  summarize(mean(uptake))
## summarize: now one row and one column, ungrouped
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `mean(uptake)`
##            <dbl>
## 1           33.5
  • What is the mean uptake for all chilled Quebec plants? Again use summarize(), but first youll want to filter the data for only chilled plants.
quebec %>%
  filter(Treatment == "chilled") %>%
  summarize(mean(uptake))
## filter: removed 21 rows (50%), 21 rows remaining
## summarize: now one row and one column, ungrouped
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `mean(uptake)`
##            <dbl>
## 1           31.8
  • Without filtering, use a single chain of commands to determine the mean uptake for both chilled and nonchilled Quebec plants. Youll need to use group_by() to setup summarize() to do calculations separately for these two groups.
quebec %>%
  group_by(Treatment) %>% #Defines how we are going to make these independent groups.
  summarize(mean(uptake))
## group_by: one grouping variable (Treatment)
## summarize: now 2 rows and 2 columns, ungrouped
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   Treatment  `mean(uptake)`
##   <fct>               <dbl>
## 1 nonchilled           35.3
## 2 chilled              31.8
  • What is the median (function median()) uptake for Quebec plants?
quebec %>%
  summarize(median(uptake))
## summarize: now one row and one column, ungrouped
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `median(uptake)`
##              <dbl>
## 1             37.2
  • What is the median uptake for Quebec plants exposed to a concentration of 500 mL/L?
quebec %>%
  filter(conc == 500) %>%
  summarize(median(uptake))
## filter: removed 36 rows (86%), 6 rows remaining
## summarize: now one row and one column, ungrouped
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `median(uptake)`
##              <dbl>
## 1             38.8
  • What is the median uptake for chilled and nonchilled Quebec plants separately exposed to a concentration of 500 mL/L?
quebec %>%
  group_by(Treatment) %>%
  filter(conc == 500) %>% #Focuses on the specified concentration.
  summarize(median(uptake))
## group_by: one grouping variable (Treatment)
## filter (grouped): removed 36 rows (86%), 6 rows remaining
## summarize: now 2 rows and 2 columns, ungrouped
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   Treatment  `median(uptake)`
##   <fct>                 <dbl>
## 1 nonchilled             40.6
## 2 chilled                38.6
  • How many plants have an uptake less than 25 when exposed to a CO2 concentration of 500 mL/L? You can answer this by piping your commands into tally() but without grouping the data - dplyr will assume all data is one group, and simply count the the number of rows!
quebec %>%
  filter(conc == 500) %>%
  tally(uptake <=25) #Counts the number of items under this criteria.
## filter: removed 36 rows (86%), 6 rows remaining
## tally: now one row and one column, ungrouped
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##       n
##   <int>
## 1     0
Question 13

Lets now compare plants from Mississippi to those from Quebec in one chain of piped commands: Which plant type has a higher mean uptake, considering only nonchilled plants exposed to a concentration of 1000 mL/L?

CO2_tibble %>%
  filter(Treatment == "nonchilled", conc == 1000) %>%
  group_by(Type) %>%
  summarize(mean(uptake))
## filter: removed 78 rows (93%), 6 rows remaining

Question 14

Now seems as good a time as any to introduce line plots. The line plot below shows the uptake (response variable) across concentrations (one of the independent variables). Note the new group aesthetic! Examine the behavior of this aesthetic by REMOVING IT ENTIRELY and seeing what the plot looks like without it specified - IT WONT WORK PROPERLY!.

### Demonstration code for making a line plot. LINE PLOTS REQUIRE THE GROUP AESTHETIC (what variable connects the points?) in order to work properly.
ggplot(CO2_tibble, aes(x = conc, y = uptake, group = Plant, color = Treatment)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  geom_point() +  ## Think: are points helpful in this plot? not help? play around by removing this geom and see what you think
  facet_grid(~Type) + 
  labs(x = "Concentration", y = "Uptake")

Using the above code as a template/concept for how to make line plots, create a line plot ONLY for CHILLED plants. This will require you to FIRST create a new tibble of only the data of interest, and then plot that data.   • First way: create your new tibble to plot and save it to a variable. Then plot from that tibble.
  • Second way: create your new tibble to plot but DO NOT save it - instead, directly pipe it into ggplot. Remember: The first argument to ggplot() is the dataframe/tibble. As an example of how this works conceptually, using iris:
  ## GUIDING EXAMPLE of piping data directly into ggplot (don't modify this code - it is an example template!)

Question 15

Make a boxplot of uptake values for all plants exposed to concentrations of 175 mL/L, where you are somehow distinguishing (colors, fills, facets, choose your adventure!) between both Treatment (chilled vs nonchilled) and Type (Quebec vs Mississippi). Make sure your figure is well-designed using principles you have learned by reading Fundamentals of Data Visualization - do not make an ugly or bad figure.

CO2_tibble %>%
  filter(conc == 175) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = uptake, fill = Treatment)) +
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.65) +
  facet_grid(~Type) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("tomato", "cyan3")) +
  labs(x = "" , y = "Uptake")

Figure to re-create

The hints you need to accomplish this task:

  • Think carefully about what variables are plotted on each axis, and devise BY HAND ON PAPER!!! a strategy for how you can manipulate the tibble to obtain these values.
  • By default, geom_bar() will automatically do counting under the hood (refer back first couple questions from More practice with ggplot2). If we want the bar height to NOT be a count, you need to use this argument geom_bar(stat="identity") - this overrides the default stat="count" which geom_bar() implicitly calls to COUNT the data! You can also use geom_col() which is equivalent to geom_bar(stat="identity").
  • Look at the X-axis - the columns are evenly spaced to represent CATEGORIES of concentrations. This occurs when you explicitly make the X-axis a factor - even though numbers are there, they will now be treated as categories. You dont have to redefine a column for this - just specify the variable as factor(variable) in your ggplot aesthetic specification rather than just variable.
  • When modifying tibbles, it is best to do any summaries AFTER all other modifications - summarizing removes columns and rows which you need to use to modify variables.

  • NOTE THE ORDER OF THE FACETS! You may have to modify variables to achieve this. Even bigger hint: You can redefine variables as factors and change their levels within a piping chain! Better yet, dont redefine but create a whole new one so, in case of problems, the original data is still there! For example with iris:

    ### Example of making a new factor variable within dplyr piping
### The first new column changes the order
### The second new column changes the order AND names of levels (labels)
iris %>%
  mutate(species_factor_custom_levels        = factor(Species, levels=c("virginica", "setosa", "versicolor")), ## change order, preserve labels
                species_factor_custom_labels = factor(Species, labels=c("Setosa", "Versicolor", "Virginica")), ## preserve order, change labels 
                species_factor_custom_levels_and_labels = factor(Species, levels=c("virginica", "setosa", "versicolor"))  ## change order, change labels
      ) -> iris2
## See the different versions of the species factor 
print(levels(iris2$Species))
## [1] "setosa"     "versicolor" "virginica"
print(levels(iris2$species_factor_custom_levels))
## [1] "virginica"  "setosa"     "versicolor"
print(levels(iris2$species_factor_custom_labels))
## [1] "Setosa"     "Versicolor" "Virginica"
print(levels(iris2$species_factor_custom_levels_and_labels))
## [1] "virginica"  "setosa"     "versicolor"


### OR A MUCH CLEANER APPROACH!!!
### Defining beforehand makes it MUCH EASIER to count parentheses!!
new_levels <-  c("virginica", "setosa", "versicolor")
new_labels <- c("Virginica", "Setosa", "Versicolor")   
iris %>%
  mutate(species_factor_custom_levels            = factor(Species, levels=new_levels), ## change order, preserve labels
                species_factor_custom_labels            = factor(Species, labels=new_labels), ## preserve order, change labels 
                species_factor_custom_levels_and_labels = factor(Species, levels=new_levels, labels = new_labels)  ## change order, change labels
        ) -> iris2    

### If you want, you could also remove the original Species from the tibble
### but, can't hurt to keep it around. really your call!
iris2 %>% select(-Species) -> iris2
